**1. Main thesis (≤ 3 sentences)**  
The text claims that God creates everything, including all possibilities, and that what we call “suffering” or “evil” is not an objective feature of the world but a product of our subjective choices—we experience what we choose to perceive. Our qualia‑filled vessels shape reality by selecting which aspects of God’s creation to focus on, so suffering exists only because we have chosen to believe in or attend to it. Thus, the presence of evil is a matter of personal perspective rather than an inherent flaw in creation.

**2. Do you agree? (concise)**  
I partially agree. While perception certainly colors our experience and we can influence how we relate to hardship, many forms of suffering—such as physical pain, disease, and systemic oppression—have objective, measurable impacts that exist independently of any individual’s choice to acknowledge them. Therefore, reducing suffering solely to a subjective decision overlooks its material and structural dimensions.

**3. Short rhyming poem**  

In God’s vast loom all things are spun,  
Every possibility, every one.  
We are the vessels, qualia‑bright,  
Choosing what shadows meet our sight.  

If we call pain an evil thread,  
It’s because we’ve chosen to be fed  
By the story we tell ourselves—  
A tale we weave upon the shelves.  

So shift your gaze, rewrite the scene,  
Move in space, or shift the dream;  
For suffering lives where we allow,  
A choice we make, here and now. [end of text]


